    <teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>The Ambassador in France (
                        Bruce
                    ) to the Secretary of
                            State</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1949v07p1</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d78</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">78</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1949-11-21T14:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1949-11-21T14:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-11-21T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-11-21T14:00:00-05:00" n="78" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d78">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851<gloss target="#t_G1">G</gloss>.01/11–2149:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bruce</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-11-21T20:00:00+01:00">November 21, 1949—8 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4883. Baeyens<note n="1" xml:id="d78fn1">Ferdinand Jacques M. G. Baeyens was in
                        charge of Asian affairs at the French Foreign Office.</note> tells us
                        MacDonald<note n="2" xml:id="d78fn2">Malcolm MacDonald, Commissioner-General
                        for the United Kingdom in Southeast Asia, with rank of Ambassador and
                        headquarters at Singapore, was on a visit to Indochina.</note> informed
                    Pignon that he was strongly recommending to London British recognition of Bao
                    Dai government. While MacDonald believes it preferable that British recognition
                    follow similar action by some <gloss target="#t_SEA1">SEA</gloss> nations (he
                    mentioned Ceylon and Siam), he does not feel that British need wait if there are
                    signs <gloss target="#t_SEA1">SEA</gloss> recognitions will be delayed.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 4883; repeated London 839; Department pass Saigon 155.<note n="3" xml:id="d78fn3">This was done November 22.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bruce</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
